{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5fdb9f6-4a94-4b42-b56e-1057cd24c971","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open Console → \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default. Enable with:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then re-run your app. Core files land in `/cores/`.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually your best starting point — it includes the crash thread, backtrace, and signal info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c7dbf1a0-ac5f-4425-8538-718c37cffb16","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"6009:36F7E:DB380E:FE9F3A:69EACAA1"},"id":"a114c219-66ee-4e51-9b72-bb278bd9190b","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:43:04.827Z","parentId":"5ae925c8-8336-4ccf-b291-2741c094f536"}
